<h2>Detailed Specification</h2>

<h3>Design</h3>

<p>
    Icons for the Design System have been sourced from Phosphor Icons (<a href="https://phosphoricons.com">https://phosphoricons.com</a>).  This icon set offers an extensive library or icons with an open license.
</p>

<p>
    To keep the Design System library small, only the most commonly used and recommended icons from the Phosphor Icons library have been bundled with the Design System.  However, you can supplement the Design System icons easily by adding icons to the Design System.
</p>

<p>
    The easiest way to add an external icon without rebuilding the Design System would be to define icon classes that follow the Design System icon naming convention and reference your custom icon files
</p>

   {% highlight "html" %}
        .jazz-icon-#{$name} {
            -webkit-mask-image: url(#{$path});
            mask-image: url($path);
        }
   {% endhighlight %}

<h3>Code</h3>
<p>
    Icons do not have any dynamic behavior.  Their styling and other characteristics are primarily derived from the underlying HTML structure.
</p>

<ul>

    <li>Icons are associated with the  <span class="code">&lti&gt</span> element.  Although this is somewhat semantically incorrect, the association with the <span class="code">&lti&gt</span> tag provides a structure that is easy for developers to remember without creating any burden on the user.</li>
    <li>Adding the <span class="code">jazz-icon</span> class to the <span class="code">&lti&gt</span> element identifies the element as an icon.</li>
    <li>The appropriate icon class is given to the <span class="code">&lti&gt</span> element to specify the icon to be used.  See the section the follows for the list of icon class names that are available.</li>
    <li>Icons take the size of the surrounding text.  By default, that would be 16px (1em).  Additional classes are available for changing the size of the icons easily (jazz-icon-2x, jazz-icon-3x, jazz-icon-5x, jazz-icon-7x, jazz-icon-9x).  Custom sizes can be achieved by setting the width and height CSS descriptors on the element.  The width of the icon should always equal the height to maintain the appropriate proportions for the image.</li>
    <li>Design System color classes can be used to change the color of icons, as can the <span class="code">color</span> CSS descriptor.</li>
    <li>In cases where an icon is paired with a corresponding label, nothing special needs to be done to support assistive devices.</li>
    <li>In cases where an icon IS NOT paired with a corresponding label, it is recommended that a visually hidden <span class="code">span</span> tag is used to wrap a label next to the icon to improve the experience for assistive devices. [i.e. <span class=”jazz-visually-hidden”>Delete</span>]</li>
</ul>

